x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Maybe because he=E2=
=80=99s from my hometown of Worcester, or maybe because we=E2=80=99re about=
 the same age, or maybe because I grew up around the corner from <b>Bob Cou=
sy </b>and have been a lifelong Celtics fan, I was absolutely entranced by =
<b>Wycliffe =E2=80=9CWyc=E2=80=9D Grousbeck</b>=E2=80=99s recent Zoom appea=
rance, alongside hedge fund manager <b>Lee Ainslie</b>, at the Economic Clu=
b of New York the other week. Grousbeck, of course, is the principal owner =
and governor of the Celtics, the reigning NBA championship franchise that h=
e purchased, along with a group of his rich friends=E2=80=94including his b=
illionaire father, <b>Irv</b>, a co-founder of Continental Cablevision=E2=
=80=94for $360 million in 2002. During his 22 years of ownership, the Celti=
cs have won two NBA rings, adding to the record 18 NBA championships the fr=
anchise has won over the years. <br/><br/>After winning the
title this past spring, Grousbeck and his partners put the team up for sale=
, hiring <b>Gregg</b> <b>Lemkau</b>, at BDT &amp; MSD Partners, and <b>Mary=
</b> <b>Erdoes</b>, at JPMorgan Chase, to run the process. It=E2=80=99s exp=
ected to fetch a boffo price of around $6 billion, one-third more than the =
$4 billion that <b>Mat</b> <b>Ishbia</b>, the billionaire mortgage maven, p=
aid for the Phoenix Suns in 2022. I can=E2=80=99t do the I.R.R. calculation=
 anymore, but I can figure out that he and his partners will likely make cl=
ose to 30 times their equity investment in the deal. That=E2=80=99s pretty =
damn impressive, and might be more than what <b>Josh</b> <b>Harris</b> and =
his posse will make on their roughly $260 million purchase of the Philadelp=
hia 76ers=E2=80=94$135 million of equity and $125 million of debt from the =
NBA=E2=80=94in 2011, should they decide to sell. <br/></td>
